Extended Time Series Analysis in R

O. Rodriguez de Rivera Ortega, PhD | University of Exeter

2025-05-21

Introduction to Time Series

cat(A time series is a set of observations recorded sequentially over time, typically at regular intervals.) cat(Time series analysis aims to understand underlying structure and forecast future values.) cat(Key components include:) cat(- Trend: long-term movement) cat(- Seasonality: systematic variation at fixed periods) cat(- Noise: random irregular variation)

Moving Average Example

cat(apply a 3-point moving average to rainfall data to smooth fluctuations and observe the trend.)

rain <- scan("http://robjhyndman.com/tsdldata/hurst/precip1.dat", skip=1)
rainseries <- ts(rain, start=c(1813))
rainseriesSMA3 <- SMA(rainseries, n=3)
plot.ts(rainseriesSMA3, main="3-Point Moving Average")

cat("Output: The plot displays a smoothed version of the rainfall time series, which helps highlight long-term trends.\n")
## Output: The plot displays a smoothed version of the rainfall time series, which helps highlight long-term trends.

Autocorrelation and Partial Autocorrelation

cat(measures correlation with lagged versions of itself.) cat(Partial autocorrelation shows the direct correlation at a given lag after controlling for intermediate lags.)

acf(rainseries, lag.max=20, main="ACF of Rainfall Series")

pacf(rainseries, lag.max=20, main="PACF of Rainfall Series")

cat("Output: Spikes outside the blue bounds indicate statistically significant autocorrelations. Useful for ARIMA modeling.\n")
## Output: Spikes outside the blue bounds indicate statistically significant autocorrelations. Useful for ARIMA modeling.

Seasonal Time Series: CO2

cat(use the built-in CO2 dataset, which records monthly atmospheric CO concentrations.)

ppmtimeseries <- ts(co2, frequency=12, start=c(1959))
plot.ts(ppmtimeseries, main="Monthly CO2 Levels at Mauna Loa")

cat("Output: This time series shows a clear upward trend and recurring seasonal fluctuations.\n")
## Output: This time series shows a clear upward trend and recurring seasonal fluctuations.

Decomposition of CO2

cat(separates the time series into trend, seasonal, and residual components.)

ppmtimeseriescomponents <- decompose(ppmtimeseries)
plot(ppmtimeseriescomponents)

cat("Output: The trend component shows long-term growth, seasonal shows repetitive yearly changes, and the remainder is noise.\n")
## Output: The trend component shows long-term growth, seasonal shows repetitive yearly changes, and the remainder is noise.

Seasonal Adjustment

cat(adjustment removes the seasonal component to better analyze the underlying trend and irregularities.)

ppmtimeseriesadjusted <- ppmtimeseries - ppmtimeseriescomponents$seasonal
plot(ppmtimeseriesadjusted, main="Seasonally Adjusted CO Series")

cat("Output: This adjusted series highlights the trend and irregular movements without seasonal interference.\n")
## Output: This adjusted series highlights the trend and irregular movements without seasonal interference.

Exponential Smoothing

cat(smoothing applies weights that decrease exponentially to past data.) cat(We use Holt-Winters smoothing without trend or seasonal components.)

rainseriesforecast <- HoltWinters(rainseries, beta=FALSE, gamma=FALSE)
plot(rainseriesforecast)

cat("Output: The fitted line smooths the rainfall series by responding more to recent values.\n")
## Output: The fitted line smooths the rainfall series by responding more to recent values.

Forecasting

cat(forecast 8 future values using the exponential smoothing model.)

rainforecast <- forecast(rainseriesforecast, h=8)
plot(rainforecast)

cat("Output: Forecasts are shown with 80% and 95% prediction intervals.\n")
## Output: Forecasts are shown with 80% and 95% prediction intervals.

Residual Diagnostics

cat(examine residuals to check if the model captured all information.)

# Residual diagnostics (handle NAs safely)
clean_residuals <- na.omit(rainforecast$residuals)

acf(clean_residuals, lag.max = 20)

Box.test(clean_residuals, lag = 20, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  clean_residuals
## X-squared = 17.401, df = 20, p-value = 0.6268
plot.ts(clean_residuals, main = "Residuals (NA removed)")

cat("Output: If residuals show no significant autocorrelation (ACF within bounds, high p-value), the model is adequate.\n")
## Output: If residuals show no significant autocorrelation (ACF within bounds, high p-value), the model is adequate.

Forecast Error Distribution

cat(compare residual distribution to a normal distribution.)

plotForecastErrors <- function(forecasterrors) {
  mybinsize <- IQR(forecasterrors, na.rm=TRUE)/4
  mysd <- sd(forecasterrors, na.rm=TRUE)
  mymin <- min(forecasterrors, na.rm=TRUE) - mysd*5
  mymax <- max(forecasterrors, na.rm=TRUE) + mysd*3
  mynorm <- rnorm(10000, mean=0, sd=mysd)
  mybins <- seq(min(mymin, min(mynorm)), max(mymax, max(mynorm)), mybinsize)
  hist(forecasterrors, col="red", freq=FALSE, breaks=mybins)
  myhist <- hist(mynorm, plot=FALSE, breaks=mybins)
  points(myhist$mids, myhist$density, type="l", col="blue", lwd=2)
}
plotForecastErrors(rainforecast$residuals)

cat("Output: The red histogram (residuals) should closely match the blue normal curve if residuals are normally distributed.\n")
## Output: The red histogram (residuals) should closely match the blue normal curve if residuals are normally distributed.

ARIMA Example: Volcanic Dust Index

cat(analyze the annual Volcanic Dust Index from 1500 onward.)

volcanodust <- scan("http://robjhyndman.com/tsdldata/annual/dvi.dat", skip=1)
volcanodustseries <- ts(volcanodust, start=c(1500))
plot.ts(volcanodustseries, main="Volcanic Dust Index")

cat("Output: The plot shows irregular spikes due to major volcanic events. The series is fairly stationary.\n")
## Output: The plot shows irregular spikes due to major volcanic events. The series is fairly stationary.

ACF/PACF for ARIMA

cat(use ACF and PACF to identify ARIMA structure.)

acf(volcanodustseries, lag.max=20)

pacf(volcanodustseries, lag.max=20)

cat("Output: Significant lags help determine AR and MA orders. For example, 2 significant lags in PACF suggests AR(2).\n")
## Output: Significant lags help determine AR and MA orders. For example, 2 significant lags in PACF suggests AR(2).

Fit ARIMA and Forecast

cat(fit an ARIMA(2,0,0) model and forecast 31 future values.)

volcano_arima <- arima(volcanodustseries, order=c(2,0,0))
volcano_forecast <- forecast(volcano_arima, h=31)
plot(volcano_forecast)

cat("Output: The forecast shows expected dust levels and confidence intervals for the next 31 years.\n")
## Output: The forecast shows expected dust levels and confidence intervals for the next 31 years.

ARIMA Residual Check

cat(check residuals from the ARIMA model to assess goodness of fit.)

acf(volcano_forecast$residuals, lag.max=20)

Box.test(volcano_forecast$residuals, lag=20, type="Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  volcano_forecast$residuals
## X-squared = 24.364, df = 20, p-value = 0.2268
plotForecastErrors(volcano_forecast$residuals)

cat("Output: Ideally, no autocorrelation and residuals are normally distributed. If so, ARIMA fit is adequate.\n")
## Output: Ideally, no autocorrelation and residuals are normally distributed. If so, ARIMA fit is adequate.
